In my latest column for the Santa Clarita Valley Signal, I shared why banning stock trading in Congress is essential to restoring trust in our government.

When I was sworn into Congress, I divested from all my company-specific, publicly traded stocks to avoid any possible conflicts of interest. Last week, I helped introduce the Restore Trust in Congress Act, bipartisan legislation that would require all members of Congress to do the same.

Restoring trust in government isn’t about partisanship, it’s about doing what’s right and putting the American people’s business first.

Today, I introduced the bipartisan Contract Postal Unit Transparency Act with @RepRickAllen. Our bill will require USPS to be transparent with communities before closing certain local post offices by publishing reports, holding public hearings, and giving residents time to make their voices heard.

In my district, the Quartz Hill Post Office, which has served our community for more than 70 years, was abruptly scheduled for closure.

Our bill will ensure families and small businesses aren’t left in the dark when USPS makes decisions that reduce their access to services.

Today, I introduced the FireGuard Reauthorization Act – important legislation that will help our firefighting capability before and during a wildfire.

Our region knows how quickly wildfires can strike and spread. In those first 24–48 hours, the National FireGuard Program provides information and data when there is very little available, using Department of Defense satellites to detect new fires and give local emergency services the information they need to act fast and save lives.

My bill will allow FireGuard to continue doing their important work for the next five years, helping local, state, and federal partners combat the wildfire crisis. 

I’ll keep fighting to strengthen our wildfire response, protect our neighborhoods, and make sure our communities have the resources we need to stay safe.

The acting head of NASA just said the agency should stop doing Earth science, a core part of its mission since the very beginning. NASA’s first mission in 1958, Explorer-1, studied Earth’s magnetic fields, and today its Earth science programs track drought, forecast severe storms, and provide data that saves lives and protects at-risk communities.

As the former Chief of Staff of NASA, I’ve seen firsthand how essential this information is for everyone from farmers to first responders, not to mention how critical it is for our national security. Space exploration and Earth science aren’t competing priorities. Both are vital, and we can’t afford to abandon either.

American consumers and businesses deserve data they can trust.

As tariffs drive inflation and unemployment increases, I introduced the Statistical Agency Integrity and Independence Act to protect economic data from political interference. https://t.co/zAXbpL94FT

As we saw this past week with the Canyon Fire in our district, accurate and timely weather forecasts aren’t just helpful, they’re lifesaving. The @NWS will now be able to hire 450 meteorologists, hydrologists, and radar technicians, restoring some of the critical capacity lost during DOGE-related staffing cuts.

These cuts severely strained our nation’s ability to forecast dangerous conditions right as we approach peak fire season in California and face extreme weather across the country.

I’ve stressed in hearings, briefings, and public statements that weather forecasting is a public safety mission. Every community depends on it, and we must ensure NOAA and NWS have the resources, staffing, and tools to meet the demands of an escalating extreme weather environment.

Yesterday, my team celebrated 105 (!) years of Lyla J. Marlett Sharpe’s life, a woman who served her country with quiet strength and purpose.

Born in Detroit in 1920, Lyla answered the call during World War II, first supporting the war effort at the Ford military plant, and then as a proud member of the groundbreaking WAVE program, helping open doors for generations of women in service.

We celebrate not just her birthday, but her incredible legacy. Thank you, Lyla, for your service and your example!

Extreme weather events are becoming more frequent and more intense as a result of climate change. Cutting our NOAA team is an absolutely terrible idea, that will leave communities far less equipped to deal with natural disasters.

NOAA employs scientists and meteorologists across an array of laboratories and forecasting offices nationwide. They share data with our local weather stations, watch our oceans and our atmospheres, and provide critical research to support billions of dollars of our economy.

NOAA provides critical, life-saving services to Americans across the country. These cuts will put you, your friends, and your family’s lives at greater risk. In California, NOAA utilizes satellite data to help us manage and address our wildfire crisis. They provide well-researched information to emergency agencies and public officials across the country to prevent natural disasters.

Dismantling the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) is straight out of the Project 2025 playbook. Americans rely on NOAA, and the National Weather Service within it, to stay safe and informed.

I have a degree in remote sensing and GIS, was NASA Chief of Staff, and now sit on the Science Committee in Congress (@sciencedems).
